1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,380
Data cleaning is centered around strategizing and decision-making

2
00:00:04,380 --> 00:00:06,750
around how you're going to deal with the issues that you

3
00:00:06,750 --> 00:00:09,300
just identified and go about fixing them.

4
00:00:09,300 --> 00:00:10,740
As part of this process,

5
00:00:10,740 --> 00:00:13,530
it's very useful and completely normal to be able

6
00:00:13,530 --> 00:00:16,890
to reuse your documentation from the assessment stage and

7
00:00:16,890 --> 00:00:19,830
continued to add to that so that you have a documentation of

8
00:00:19,830 --> 00:00:23,745
your thought process as you're approaching cleaning some of these issues.

9
00:00:23,745 --> 00:00:26,040
Now let's go ahead and take a look at a couple of

10
00:00:26,040 --> 00:00:29,730
complex issues that data wranglers deal with when they have to clean data.

11
00:00:29,730 --> 00:00:33,660
Sometimes it can be more complicated to strategize data.

12
00:00:33,660 --> 00:00:37,695
Let's talk about a few complex cleaning tasks that you would need to make a decision

13
00:00:37,695 --> 00:00:42,240
on based on your assessment and your experience around the domain and problem statement.

14
00:00:42,240 --> 00:00:44,825
These issues are dealing with outliers,

15
00:00:44,825 --> 00:00:47,750
dealing with duplicates, and dealing with missing data.

16
00:00:47,750 --> 00:00:49,565
Let's start with outliers.

17
00:00:49,565 --> 00:00:52,100
An outlier is a data point that is considerably

18
00:00:52,100 --> 00:00:55,430
distinct and somewhat of an anomaly from other data samples.

19
00:00:55,430 --> 00:00:58,345
For example, take a look at this bar plot on the screen.

20
00:00:58,345 --> 00:01:00,890
Notice how the bar to the right of the plot at a value

21
00:01:00,890 --> 00:01:03,245
of 120 is distinct from the other data points,

22
00:01:03,245 --> 00:01:04,670
which makes it an outlier.

23
00:01:04,670 --> 00:01:09,080
We define outliers as points that are lying beyond the range that we determine.

24
00:01:09,080 --> 00:01:12,630
Some outliers are a result of mistakes and should be removed.

25
00:01:12,630 --> 00:01:17,390
For example, a student's age being 120 is impossible and should be removed.

26
00:01:17,390 --> 00:01:23,115
Notice how the typical range of students ages for this data set is between 12-15.

27
00:01:23,115 --> 00:01:26,870
But what is this data set was reflecting overall human age.

28
00:01:26,870 --> 00:01:29,430
It's possible for a person to live up to 120,

29
00:01:29,430 --> 00:01:32,575
so the outlier would actually be a correct data point.

30
00:01:32,575 --> 00:01:35,765
If you consider outliers as part of your analysis,

31
00:01:35,765 --> 00:01:40,735
it can often skew summary statistics like your mean and prolong your visualizations.

32
00:01:40,735 --> 00:01:44,540
However, outliers can also represent valuable information

33
00:01:44,540 --> 00:01:48,245
about certain groups of your data that just aren't like the rest of the data,

34
00:01:48,245 --> 00:01:50,720
which may be worth further investigation.

35
00:01:50,720 --> 00:01:55,190
Data wranglers deal with outliers by defining the range that they care about.

36
00:01:55,190 --> 00:01:57,470
They may use information such as the results of

37
00:01:57,470 --> 00:02:00,940
the dot info function from pandas to quickly diagnose issues.

38
00:02:00,940 --> 00:02:02,750
For example, from this information,

39
00:02:02,750 --> 00:02:05,750
we can quickly pinpoint that a min-weight of 48 pounds and

40
00:02:05,750 --> 00:02:09,095
a height of 27 inches does not immediately make sense.

41
00:02:09,095 --> 00:02:12,290
We can then use the min function and sort values functions in

42
00:02:12,290 --> 00:02:16,465
pandas to pinpoint which row is causing this issue and take action.

43
00:02:16,465 --> 00:02:19,505
In order to detect outliers programmatically,

44
00:02:19,505 --> 00:02:23,160
data wranglers can establish boundaries of the typical range of data points,

45
00:02:23,160 --> 00:02:26,990
so any points that fall out of that boundaries are outliers.

46
00:02:26,990 --> 00:02:29,910
There are two common methods to detect outliers.

47
00:02:29,910 --> 00:02:32,475
The first approach is using standard deviation.

48
00:02:32,475 --> 00:02:34,775
For example saying mean plus or minus

49
00:02:34,775 --> 00:02:37,910
one standard deviation are the upper and lower outlier boundaries.

50
00:02:37,910 --> 00:02:42,145
Any data points that are falling outside of this range will be outliers.

51
00:02:42,145 --> 00:02:45,455
Second, using the interquartile range method,

52
00:02:45,455 --> 00:02:47,180
we can also detect outliers.

53
00:02:47,180 --> 00:02:49,805
Let me briefly describe how we can use this method

54
00:02:49,805 --> 00:02:52,895
both visually and programmatically through a boxplot.

55
00:02:52,895 --> 00:02:56,180
We can first calculate the interquartile range value by

56
00:02:56,180 --> 00:03:00,820
subtracting the upper quartile or Q3 from the lower quartile or Q1.

57
00:03:00,820 --> 00:03:05,750
We then calculate the lower bound by subtracting Q1 with 1.5,

58
00:03:05,750 --> 00:03:07,820
multiply it by the IQR, and similarly,

59
00:03:07,820 --> 00:03:11,845
the upper bound is Q3 plus 1.5 times the IQR.

60
00:03:11,845 --> 00:03:16,790
Any values that lie outside the range of our lower to upper bound are outliers.

61
00:03:16,790 --> 00:03:20,015
Visually, box plots can help us quickly grasp whether

62
00:03:20,015 --> 00:03:24,355
outliers are beyond the minimum or the maximum values in the range.

63
00:03:24,355 --> 00:03:26,570
Then data wrangler is may remove

64
00:03:26,570 --> 00:03:29,255
the outliers they have determined to be inaccurate completely,

65
00:03:29,255 --> 00:03:32,150
or remove the outliers temporarily in order to get

66
00:03:32,150 --> 00:03:35,315
summary statistics and keep these outliers separate,

67
00:03:35,315 --> 00:03:41,010
or keep the outliers in the analysis and treat them as regular data points.

